just_use hint.go

# label: EARLY
# role: encodes domain knowledge

Hint orchestration — the new system, rebuilt from scratch
2026-04-18. Walks `HintPriorityOrder` (the seven tricks in
simplest-first order), asks each for plays, takes the FIRST
play per trick as a `Suggestion`, returns the combined list
ranked by priority position.

No scoring metric. No enumeration. No retroactive attribution.
The ordering IS the ranking.

**Priority order** (from simplest/most-visually-obvious to
most-strategic):

1. `direct_play` — one hand card extends a stack (the
   beginner-favorite).
2. `hand_stacks` — hand already contains a run or set.
   Internal sub-order: pure runs → rb runs → sets.
3. `pair_peel` — two hand cards form a pair, peel one board
   card to complete.
4. `split_for_set` — one hand card + two same-value peeled
   board cards.
5. `peel_for_run` — one hand card + V-1 + V+1 peeled cards.
6. `rb_swap` — substitute a hand card into an existing rb run.
7. `loose_card_play` — move a board card so a stranded hand
   card can play. Last resort.

**Wire shape.** `BuildSuggestions` returns `[]Suggestion`; each
entry has `rank`, `trick_id`, `description`, `hand_cards`,
`action`. Action is a ready-to-POST wire shape:

- `direct_play` → `merge_hand` action (target_stack + side
  reconstructed from the before/after board diff).
- Everything else → `trick_result` action with pre-diffed
  `stacks_to_remove` + `stacks_to_add` + `hand_cards_released`.

**Server over-shares.** The list carries ALL firing tricks'
suggestions. Client picks rank=1 in the common case; a
strategic bot can look deeper.

See `showell/claude_writings/hints_from_first_principles.md`
for the full design rationale.
